Twitter Search
By: Ziad Matni

usage: tw_search.py [-h] [-g LOCA] [-l L] [-t T] [-c C] [-o OUT [OUT ...]] query

Twitter Search

positional arguments:
  query             Search term string

optional arguments:
  -h, --help        show this help message and exit
  -g LOCA           Location (lo, nyl, nym, nyu, dc, sf, nb)    DEFAULT = None 
  -l L              Language (en = English, fr = French, etc.)  DEFAULT = en
  -t T              Search type: mixed, recent, or popular      DEFAULT = recent
  -c C              Tweet count (must be <15)                   DEFAULT = 1
  -d D              Output destination: (sc)reen or (db)        DEFAULT = sc
  -o OUT [OUT ...]  Output options: ca, tx, id, co, rtc         DEFAULT = [ca, tx]

A note on the -o option:
This allows the user to output one of 6 popular pieces of Twitter metadata:
    ca  created_at date
    tx  text
    id  ID number
    co  coordinates (if any)
    rtc retweet count (if any)
The output (-o) option defaults to the created_at date and the tweet text.

